</pre>
<h1><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: Course">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-headl=
ine" id=3D"Course"> Course </span></h1>
<p>Building PSTN Gateways, SIP Trunks, and CUBEs for Cisco Collaboration (3=
00-070) CIPTV1
</p>
<h1><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: Chapter">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-head=
line" id=3D"Chapter"> Chapter </span></h1>
<p>How to read SIP messages
</p>
<h1><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: Introducci=C3=B3n">editar</a>]</span> <span class=
=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"Introducci.C3.B3n"> Introducci=C3=B3n </span></h1>
<p><a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/index.php/Archivo:20180804_01.png"=
 class=3D"image"><img alt=3D"20180804 01.png" src=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telef=
onia/images/8/85/20180804_01.png" width=3D"777" height=3D"385"></a>
</p><p>We are going to examine how SIP uses request, responses, and SDP (Se=
ssion Description Protocol). <br>
</p><p>Once we know how it works, we can use this information to read SIP m=
esasges. <br>
</p><p>SIP was created by an organization called the IETF (Internet Enginee=
ring Task Force) and this means that it supports IP features like DNS. <br>
</p><p>Its puprpose is to set up, modify, and tear down sessions. And by se=
ssions, we mean IP phone calls or video sessions between end devices that u=
se video. <br>
</p>
<h1><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: Request - Response Transaction Model between endpo=
ints called User Agents">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-headline" id=
=3D"Request_-_Response_Transaction_Model_between_endpoints_called_User_Agen=
ts"> Request - Response Transaction Model between endpoints called User Age=
nts </span></h1>
<p>SIP uses a transaction model between endpoints called user agents. And t=
he transactions that it uses are requests and responses. <br>
</p><p>There are a few different types of user agents, and they are going t=
o depend on who is doing the requesting and who is doing the responding. <b=
r>
<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/index.php/Archivo:20180804_02.png" cl=
ass=3D"image"><img alt=3D"20180804 02.png" src=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefoni=
a/images/f/f7/20180804_02.png" width=3D"933" height=3D"339"></a>
<br>
The user agent client is a SIP device that sends out a request. <br>
For instance, if you make a phone call, you pick up your Cisco IP phone and=
 dial a number, you are going to send out a SIP invite.<br>
That is a request. So the IP phone is the SIP user agent client. Well that =
invite is going to go to the Cisco Unified Communications Manager cluster, =
and they have to respond. <br>
When a SIP device receives a request, it has to send a response and that ma=
kes it a SIP user agent server. <br>
</p><p>Keep in mind that a single device can be both user client and user a=
gent server. <br>
In our example when you make a phone call, your phone sends out the invite,=
 that is the client, the Unified Communications Manager responds, they are =
the server, but the Unified Communications Manager server is going to send =
out its own request. It is going to pass on our invite somewhere. And becau=
se of that, it becomes a user agent client itself. So one device can do bot=
h. It is simply a matther of who is doing the requesting and who is doing t=
he responding. <br>
</p>
<h1><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: SIP Messages - Requests">editar</a>]</span> <span =
class=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"SIP_Messages_-_Requests"> SIP Messages - Reques=
ts </span></h1>
<p>One of the most useful characteristics of SIP is that it is not just Cis=
co SIP or some other vendor SIP, it is just SIP. <br>
SIP is made up of messages. It uses request and responses. <br>
We are going to start with going over the most popular SIP requests. Undest=
anding these various SIP request will be really beneficial when configuring=
 SIP devices and troubleshooting SIP deployments when things do not go as p=
lanned. <br>
I know that going over list is not a lot of fun, but it is important that w=
e understand what these SIP request are and what they do because we are goi=
ng to see them often. <br>
These are some of the most common SIP requests. <br>
<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/index.php/Archivo:20180804_03.png" cl=
ass=3D"image"><img alt=3D"20180804 03.png" src=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefoni=
a/images/e/e0/20180804_03.png" width=3D"1167" height=3D"625"></a>
<br>
<br>
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: INVITE">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-headl=
ine" id=3D"INVITE">INVITE </span></h2>
<p>And invite request is when we make a phone call. The user agent client s=
ends out an invite, and he is asking the other side, Hey, do you want to ha=
ve a call&nbsp;?
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: ACK">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-headline=
" id=3D"ACK"> ACK </span></h2>
<p>An ack is used after we receive a final response. <br>
When we send an invite, that is a request. The other side, the user agent s=
erver, has to give us a response. <br>
It can be a success or a failure, but they have to give us a reply. When th=
ey do, the ack is returned. We send the ack to the server letting them know=
 that we got their response.
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: BYE">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-headline=
" id=3D"BYE"> BYE </span></h2>
<p>A bye request is when we hang up. <br>
You have made a phone call, you are talking to whoever, and you decide, Wel=
l, I am done. And you hang up the call. <br>
Whoever hangs up will send out a SIP bye request. <br>
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: CANCEL">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-headl=
ine" id=3D"CANCEL"> CANCEL </span></h2>
<p>A cancel request cancels before the other side answers, before we receiv=
e a final response. <br>
Maybe you pick up the phone to call somebody, It is rtinging, and you chang=
e your mind, so yo hang up. <br>
You would send out a cancel request.
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: OPTIONS">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-head=
line" id=3D"OPTIONS"> OPTIONS </span></h2>
<p>The SIP options request allows a client to discover information about th=
e supported capabilities like what codecs do you support. And it can do thi=
s without ringing the other party.
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: REGISTER">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-hea=
dline" id=3D"REGISTER"> REGISTER </span></h2>
<p>The SIP register request --this is used by SIP phones to register to the=
ir call agent or the Cisco Unified Communication Manager server.
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: SUBSCRIBER">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-h=
eadline" id=3D"SUBSCRIBER"> SUBSCRIBER </span></h2>
<p>A subscriber request is when a device wants to know when somethings happ=
ens. <br>
A SIP phone might subscribe to a voicemail server in order to be notified w=
hen there is a voicemail so that it can turn its red light on or its messag=
e waiting indicator light. It would subscribe to that event.
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: NOTIFY">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-headl=
ine" id=3D"NOTIFY"> NOTIFY </span></h2>
<p>The SIP notify mesage is a way to tell the subscriber that the event tha=
t they have subscribed to has ocurred. <br>
ur SIP IP phone has subscribed to the Unity Connection server voicemail sys=
tem. It wants to know when it receives a voicemail.<br>
Well, when the voicemail shows up, the Unity Connection server sends out a =
SIP notify mesage telling the SIP phone, Hey, you voicemail showed up. Go a=
head and turn on your messager waiting indicator light. <br>
We will also see SIP notify messages as a way to carry DTMF digits, dual-to=
ne multi-frequency. Some codecs can not support sending digits in the middl=
e of a call. <br>
You are on the phone, and want to check your bank balance, and it ask you t=
o put in your account number. You start pressing digits and nothings happen=
s because the codec that your are using can not support sending those digit=
s over the call.<br>
SIP notify is a way that the SIP phone can notify the server, Hey, we are p=
ressing the #7, the #5, and that is KPML, or key press markup language.
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: PUBLISH">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-head=
line" id=3D"PUBLISH"> PUBLISH </span></h2>
<p>A SIP publish request is used when a service has something to report. Wh=
en a voicemail server wants to report a new voicemail, it sends a publish m=
esage that contains informations about the voicemail and the caller who lef=
t it.=20
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: UPDATE">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-headl=
ine" id=3D"UPDATE"> UPDATE </span></h2>
<p>A SIP update message modifies the state of a  session before the other s=
ide answers, before final response is received. <br>
For example, maybe you are going to adjust call duration timers during call=
 setup.
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: MESSAGE">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-head=
line" id=3D"MESSAGE"> MESSAGE </span></h2>
<p>A message request transports instant messages using SIP. We see this wit=
h Cisco Jabber. <br>
It is a tool that allows us to not only make phone calls, but we can send I=
M and instant messages to other users using SIP messages request.=20
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: REFER">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-headli=
ne" id=3D"REFER"> REFER </span></h2>
<p>A SIP refer request allows you to move an active session from one endpoi=
nt to the other. <br>
We see these with call transfers.<br>
<br>
These are the most common SIP requests. There are more, and you can go find=
 lists, and they will have all of the SIP requests.
</p>
<h1><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: SIP Messages - Responses">editar</a>]</span> <span=
 class=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"SIP_Messages_-_Responses"> SIP Messages - Resp=
onses </span></h1>
<p>SIP is basically a call and response protocol. You send a message, you g=
et a response. <br>
In some situations, you might even get multiple responses for a single requ=
est message such as when we send out an invite request. And we will see som=
e examples of that soon. <br>
A SIP response is more than just simply an acknowledgement to a request. It=
 carries with it useful information back to the user agent client, the devi=
ce that sent out the request. <br>
Response message fall into six different classes or categories, and they ar=
e identified with a three-digit number value. <br>
We are going to examine the six different types of response messages so tha=
t we can easily identify them and understand what each one does. <br>
</p><p><a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/index.php/Archivo:20180804_07.=
png" class=3D"image"><img alt=3D"20180804 07.png" src=3D"http://10.3.1.52/t=
elefonia/images/b/b8/20180804_07.png" width=3D"927" height=3D"308"></a>
<br>
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: Provisional 100">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D=
"mw-headline" id=3D"Provisional_100"> Provisional 100 </span></h2>
<p>The first type of response is a provisional 100 level response. And this=
 means, Hey, I heard your request. I am working on it. Give me some time, g=
ive me a few moments. <br>
The user agent client sends out a request like an invite. The user agent se=
rver receives the request, and it needs to process it and look up and figur=
e out where to send your request and what to do with it. <br>
But in the meantime, it sends back right away a 100 level response. And it =
just simply tells the user agent client, Hey, sit tight. I heard your reque=
st. I am working on it. Give some time. <br>
When the user agent client receives the provisional response, it does not a=
cknowledge it. It just kind of waits for some information.
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: 200 level success">editar</a>]</span> <span class=
=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"200_level_success"> 200 level success </span></h2>
<p>The next type of response is a 200 level success response. This means th=
at your request was received, undestood and accepted. Two hundred level res=
ponses are final responses. <br>
In fact, all of the responses except 100 level are considered final. <br>
When a user agent client sends out a request and receives a final response,=
 whether it be a 200 success or another type, since it's final, the user ag=
ent client sends out an ack request letting the server know, I received you=
r final response.
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: 300 level redirect">editar</a>]</span> <span class=
=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"300_level_redirect"> 300 level redirect </span></h2>
<p>A 300 level SIP response is a redirect. It means further action is neede=
d. We will see these with SIP proxies.<br>
The user agent client sends out an invite, and if there is a proxy in the p=
ath, the proxy receives the invite, and it does not know the IP address of =
the phone you are trying to reach. That is not its job. <br>
Proxies have a lot of jobs and one of them is to know the IP address or the=
 DNS name of a server that can help you with your request. So it sends back=
 a final response, a 300 redirection message telling the user agent client =
where to go next.
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: 400 level">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-he=
adline" id=3D"400_level"> 400 level </span></h2>
<p>When a user agent server sends back a 400 level SIP response it means th=
at the request was not able to be fulfilled. It failed. <br>
But more than that it can tell us where and possibly why the call failed be=
cause a 400 level response means there is a client error. <br>
The client did something wrong. maybe the user agent client dialed the wron=
g number or it needs to be authenticated. <br>
for example, we have all received 404 errors when we have put the wrong add=
ress into a web browser. Well, SIP uses the same type of responses. In fact=
, you will see that you will get a 400 response when you dial the wrong num=
ber. <br>
Often the user agent server will include a reason or a text along with the =
400 level response and this can point us to the exact cause of the failure.
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D24" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: 500 level">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-he=
adline" id=3D"500_level"> 500 level </span></h2>
<p>A 500 level SIP response means there is an error with the user agent ser=
ver. There are a variety of reasons that this could happen. <br>
Maybe there is an internal error or the service that we are trying to reach=
 is unavailable. <br>
A 500 level SIP response means that the user agent client sent a valid SIP =
request but something is not right with the user agent server.=20
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: 600 level">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-he=
adline" id=3D"600_level"> 600 level </span></h2>
<p>A 600 level SIP response means there is a global failure. The request ca=
n not be fulfilled by any server. <br>
We have sent a valid request and maybe the user agent server is okay, but f=
or some reason beyond that our call is not going to work or our request can=
 not be fulfilled. <br>
That can be because maybe all possible destinations are busy. Or the device=
 we are trying to reach does not want to talk to us. <br>
Maybe the have got their presence set to Do Not Disturb or Out To Lunch. <b=
r>
We have examined SIP messages. We have seen the most common SIP requests. A=
nd we have gone through the different classes of SIP responses. <br>
Now we are going to look at a SIP call diagram that we can see the request =
and responses in action.
</p>
<h1><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: SDP Session Description Protocol">editar</a>]</spa=
n> <span class=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"SDP_Session_Description_Protocol"> SDP=
 Session Description Protocol </span></h1>
<p>SDP (Session Description Protocol), is used with SIP to set up parameter=
s of a multimedia session, the audio or video call. <br>
We have seen how SIP works. One side sends an invite, and the other side ha=
s to respond. <br>
But what exactly are we inviting them to&nbsp;? <br>
Here we have an example of what a session description protocol and SDP offe=
r could look like, and it is an offer. It is not a negotiation. <br>
<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/index.php/Archivo:20180804_04.png" cl=
ass=3D"image"><img alt=3D"20180804 04.png" src=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefoni=
a/images/1/16/20180804_04.png" width=3D"854" height=3D"482"></a>
<br>
<br>
2001 is calling 3001.The user agent client of Cisco Unified Communication M=
anager cluster A sends a SIP invite. The invite contains an SDP offer. <br>
This make it SIP early offer. If the initial invite contains the offer for =
the media (SDP), then that is called early offer. <br>
Let's look at one line from this SDP example, the M line. This simply defin=
es the media that is being offered: source port 16444. And the real-time pr=
otocol/audio-video profile 18 and 101. <br>
That is the media that is being offered. And basically that just means the =
codec type (G729) and then the 101 represents how we will send DTMF digits =
during the active call. <br>
Here we have the session description protocol answer. <br>
<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/index.php/Archivo:20180804_05.png" cl=
ass=3D"image"><img alt=3D"20180804 05.png" src=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefoni=
a/images/1/15/20180804_05.png" width=3D"857" height=3D"485"></a>
<br>
<br>
When 3001 accepts the call, the 200 OK response is sent. This contains the =
answer to the SDP offer. <br>
If you are going to have an audio voice call, both sides needs to agree on =
the codec. <br>
SDP answers are required in order to have a successful call. <br>
SDP is one of the first things that I examine when troubleshooting the SIP =
call. I want to know what type of call is being offered and accepted. <br>
If one side is trying to set up a voice call using a codec that the other s=
ite can not support or company policy does not allow due to bandwidth restr=
iction, then that is going to show up here. <br>
Let's take a look at what each line of the session description protocol rep=
resents. <br>
We are going to examine the various headers that make up a session descript=
ion protocol offer.=20
</p>
<h2><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: Headers">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-head=
line" id=3D"Headers"> Headers </span></h2>
<p>Keep in mind that some of the information that is contained in a SDP off=
er will depend on the devices that are involved in the call. <br>
SDP offers are made on a call-by-call basis. <br>
Some devices have different options and support different codecs and featur=
es. <br>
<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/index.php/Archivo:20180804_06.png" cl=
ass=3D"image"><img alt=3D"20180804 06.png" src=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefoni=
a/images/f/fb/20180804_06.png" width=3D"938" height=3D"531"></a>
</p>
<h3><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: v header">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-hea=
dline" id=3D"v_header"> v header </span></h3>
<p>This is the protocol version number, which is currently set to 0.
</p>
<h3><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: Originator and session identifier">editar</a>]</sp=
an> <span class=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"Originator_and_session_identifier"> O=
riginator and session identifier </span></h3>
<p>This is the username, ID, version number, network address. <br>
In this example, we have got CiscoSystemCCM (Cisco Unified Communication Ma=
nager), SIP because we are using SIP trunk, and the 11 is the version of th=
e Cisco Unified Communications Manager server. <br>
The IP4 address 10.2.5.15 is the IP address of the server that has the SIP =
trunk that is sending up the SIP offer. <br>
</p>
<h3><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: connection offer">editar</a>]</span> <span class=
=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"connection_offer"> connection offer </span></h3>
<p>The c is the connection offer, and I kind of think of it as the contact.=
 <br>
Notice the IP address is different. This is the phone.<br>
The SDP is being sent by the Unified Communication Manager server out of th=
e SIP trunk. It's sending the invite and the SDP offer on behalf  of the ph=
one. <br>
But the actual media, which is what the SDP is describing, is not going to =
the Unified Communication Manager server, it's going to the phone, the end =
point. <br>
So the SDP contains the IP address of who is going to get the media stream =
that the SDP is describing. <br>
This is the IP address of the IP phone that is making the call.=20
</p>
<h3><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: t header">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-hea=
dline" id=3D"t_header"> t header </span></h3>
<p>Is the time and there is not time limit that is being added to this. <br=
>
So the SDP is describing the session that is being offered the actual phone=
 call, and if you wanted to limit the amount of time that this could be act=
ive, you could put that int the t. But we are not limiting that at all, so =
the t is set to 0 0. <br>
</p>
<h3><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D32" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: m line">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-headl=
ine" id=3D"m_line"> m line </span></h3>
<p>Is the crucial line. This header line describes the media. <br>
In this case we are offering an audio session, a VoIP call, and the source =
port is going to be 24688. <br>
The real-time protocol/audio-video profile that is being offered are the co=
decs. Well it's offering 18 and 101. <br>
You might not know what 18 and 101 are, but that is okay because SDP includ=
es their definition in the SDP headers. <br>
And that is what the remaining lines are. They describe the m line. <br>
</p>
<h3><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D33" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: Attributes">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-h=
eadline" id=3D"Attributes"> Attributes </span></h3>
<h4><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D34" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: rtpmap">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-headl=
ine" id=3D"rtpmap"> rtpmap </span></h4>
<p>rtpmap:18 (real-time protocol map) defines what was in the m line as 18.=
 It simply list that as G729. <br>
That is the RTP codec type, the payload type of 18 is G729. <br>
The 8000 represents how many bits. G729 uses 8000 bits a second for audio. =
<br>
</p>
<h4><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D35" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: packetization time">editar</a>]</span> <span class=
=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"packetization_time"> packetization time </span></h4>
<p>Packetization time; 20 represents 20 msec. <br>
Well, 1000 msec is 1 second, so something that is 20 msec is 1/50th of a se=
cond. <br>
This means that we want to use G729 50 packets a second. Each packet contai=
ns 1/50th of the audio or 20 msec of time.=20
</p>
<h4><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D36" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: sendrecv">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D"mw-hea=
dline" id=3D"sendrecv"> sendrecv </span></h4>
<p>The sendrecv attribute, this is normal when you have an audio call. <br>
If you were to put somebody on hold, you could send a new invite to them, a=
nd it would have a new SDP offer that says send only. <br>
And then they would receive that, and they could accept with the SDP that s=
ays receive only. <br>
When you are debugging and you examine SDPs, if you see either one of those=
, send or receive only, you know that the user is put on hold.
A sendrecv together is just the standard attribute offered for two-way call=
. <br>=20
</p>
<h4><span class=3D"editsection">[<a href=3D"http://10.3.1.52/telefonia/inde=
x.php?title=3DCategor%C3%ADa:SIP&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D37" title=
=3D"Editar secci=C3=B3n: rtpmap and fmtp">editar</a>]</span> <span class=3D=
"mw-headline" id=3D"rtpmap_and_fmtp"> rtpmap and fmtp </span></h4>
<p>The last two attributes go together. They are one way that SIP handles t=
he sending and receiving of DTMF (dual-tone multifrequency) digits during a=
 call. <br>
When you press a button during a call it creates a sound. That sound is cod=
ed and put into RTP packets using codecs. <br>
The problem is that some codecs are not very good an interpreting what butt=
on we press. Some gateways are not very good at this either. <br>
Here SIP offers one possible solution. When you press a digit on a phone, s=
end them in a separate stream and mark the packet with an RTP payload type =
of 101 versus the RTP payload type of 18 that G729 uses. <br>
The last line says that the device will use an RTP payload type of 101 if a=
ny buttons 0-15 are pressed. And 0-15 is 0 through 9, *, #, A, B, C or D. <=
br>
Its purpose is to create a separate path for transporting DTMF digits. And =
this allows the audio codec to focus on just sending and receiving the call=
 audio. <br>
</p>
